The area

Address
Neighborhood: Navona / Pantheon / Campo de’ Fiori
With three of Rome’s most beloved piazzas within a five-minute walk of each other, the Navona / Pantheon / Campo area may be the prettiest and most picturesque area of the city. Join the beautiful throngs hanging out in cafes, boutiques, art galleries, and wine bars, or peek at a neighborhood museum or monument. If you want nonstop movida, the streets here are busy with chic bicyclists and Vespa drivers, street vendors, merchants, and locals. There is no rhyme or reason to its winding streets and there's something to see around every corner, so take pleasure in a spontaneous wander.

    Jesuit Flagship Church
    This is the flagship church of the Jesuits, filled with beautiful paintings, artwork, sculptures, and holy relics including St Francis Xavier’s arm and the body of St Ignatius, the 16th century founder of the Jesuits. There's no shortage of marble, gold, silver and other precious materials like lapis lazuli. It's impressive but it’s even more so, if you are there for the guest appearance of St Ignatius. Every afternoon (around 5:30pm) a silver and gold, jewel-studded statue of St Ignatius theatrically appears. Most of the time, he is hidden behind a panel with a rather dull, unremarkable painting of St Ignatius in his black Jesuit robes. However once a day, the panel slowly slides down to reveal the statue behind. The lighting drops, music plays throughout the church and when the lighting comes back on, St Ignatius is standing with outstretched arms, looking up toward Heaven. One of the things that I like about this church is that it doesn’t get crowds of tourists so it’s quite a peaceful place to be. If you have the time, it is also worth looking at the very humble, almost stark rooms of St Ignatius which have been preserved next to the church. Entry is free (donation optional).
    Visited July 2023
    Traveled as a couple

Mother Church of the Jesuits
Mar 2024 • Family
This is the Mother Church of the Jesuits Society and model of an uncountable number of Jesuit churches built around the world. It also considered the very first church constructed in what is known as Baroque architectural style (1568-80) which from here spread throughout the city of Rome, around Italy, Europe and then the rest of the Catholic World.

The church is located at a small square by the same name in the heart of the city centre. Opening hours are 7.30am to 12.30pm (morning) and 4-7.30pm (afternoon) daily and is free to enter and visit. Within, visitors are treated to a Baroque splendour with nave, chapels main altar, apse and inner dome heavily adorned with frescos, gilding and ornamentation. A highlight is the remarkable ceiling fresco called 'Triumph of the Name of Jesus' by Giovanni Battista Gaulli (1678-79). You can use the mirror in centre of the nave to view the ceiling fresco. The sculpture known as 'Religion Overthrowing Heresy and Hatred' by sculpture Pierre Le Gros the younger (1695-99) is another remarkable work amongst so many other impressive features within the church.

In the end, the Church of Gesu is not just a Baroque gem, it is an important historic attraction and such a beautiful place to spend precious sightseeing time in Rome. It is one of my favourite churches in the city, a place we always make sure to pass by at least once during visits to the city.
Written April 29, 2024

Yes you can walk into the Church directly - it is even free. But because no tourist visits during Mass (Mon-Sat 7:45 AM, 9:00 AM, 12:00 noon, 7:00 PM and also Sundays and Holy Days 8:00 AM, 10:00 AM, 11:30 AM, 7:00 PM) and in addition the church is closed during the hottest part of the day (12:30 PM to 4:00 PM) then your best bet is Mon-Fri around 11:00 AM or between 4:00 PM and 7:00 PM.
